posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked: I was wondering how thick polycarbonate should be to sustain an impact from a coral being dropped on it from the high heights that robots are extending to. Is 1/8‚Äù sufficient or would we need to have it be 1/4‚Äù?

posts.name: Brendan Simons, 5406
posts.cooked:
It will depend on how you support the plastic sheet.  The best answer might be to test what you have (use something other than a good Rio add your test dummy).

Here‚Äôs another option for you that might be the best of both worlds: 1/4" hollow currogated polycarbonate.
I would generally avoid 1/8th polycarb. It can be broken by hand which will result in a really bad day.

posts.name: Jon K.
posts.cooked: 1/8‚Äù polycarb should not break by hand. You probably used acrylic. When I was at AndyMark, I did a video on this. Using .06‚Äù thick poly, I could fold it, but it didn‚Äôt break.
It was absolutely PC and corners could be broken off by pliers in the usual PC failure mode and had the dark edges, but parts made of it could be broken by hand.

posts.name: ben gates
posts.cooked: you can easily get away with 1/16" or 1/8" polycarb if you implement it correctly. sheet materials get significantly stiffer if their edges have bends (to an extent, depends how large your sheet is). if you‚Äôre designing a brain pan, try arching the entire pan like a turtle shell to protect from high impacts

posts.name: Nick Foote
posts.cooked:
The two easiest ways to tell if something is polycarb or acrylic:

It‚Äôs Acrylic if it breaks or shatters easily, and if you can cut it with a laser cutter and it has nice smooth edges.

It‚Äôs Polycarb if it bends, and only breaks if it gets hit on stress points (like drilled holes) very hard on the edge (not the face), and if you try to laser cut it, it puts out more dark toxic fumes than Mount Doom.

As for protection, it‚Äôs just a massive ‚Äúdepends‚Äù.

Depends on how big of an unsupported area it‚Äôs covering

Depends how far down the electronics are from the polycarb (if they are right up against it, bad. if they are a few inches down, better)

Depends what angle the polycarb is at (flat means entire impact is hitting down, slanted means impact is redirected sideways, vertical means it only protects from side hits)

The real answer is, use as thick of stuff as you can while still getting under 115 lbs.

posts.name: philso
posts.cooked:
We have two 1/8" thick polycarbonate protective panels over our control system.

One measures 28" x 14" and is installed vertically on a 2x1 tube frame.

The second is over the rear section and measures about 26" x 8". There is a 1" wide flange on one of the long sides and a 2" wide flange on the other long side. The 2" flange supports the panel so it is over our swerve modules. The flanges were bent on a sheet metal brake and greatly stiffen the panel. With the flanges, the panel is more than sufficiently stiff to withstand an impact from a falling Coral.

posts.name: Gus Michel II
posts.cooked: I take it you score the CORAL on the rear of the robot?

posts.name: philso
posts.cooked: Yes. That is also the side we pluck the Algae off the Reef. It is possible that a robot scoring a Coral next to us drops it on our robot.

posts.name: Dan
posts.cooked:
We have gotten away with 0.093" (so less than 1/8") bent polycarbonate for several years. This rapid react robot took full hits from other robots on the side and top, and never broke. Attachment was 1/8 in rivets and screwed into the chassis.
